{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488809","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488809"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:58:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:58:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"547"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"547","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/547"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.22,0.03,0.24,0.44,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"547"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97783"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"547","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/547"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"547"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80338"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1200"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2982"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3029"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13982"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97783","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/97783"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 69-year-old woman attends a follow-up oncology clinic. She has recently had a CT scan to assess whether there has been any change to her known malignancy, for which she has been receiving treatment for three years. She reports her health as being the same as when she was last seen. Whilst she does have noticeable abdominal distension, this does not bother her or interfere with her life unduly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAs on her last assessment some six months ago, on examination there are palpable masses within her abdominal cavity and a palpable liver edge. These findings have not changed since her last examination. The CT findings are as they were 18 months earlier and report stable disease (Images 1, 2).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely underlying diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Gastric adenocarcinoma","Lung squamous cell carcinoma","Neuroendocrine tumour","Hepatocellular carcinoma","Renal cell carcinoma"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EOf all the malignant diseases listed, a \u003Cstrong\u003Egrade 1 neuroendocrine tumour \u003C/strong\u003Eis the most likely diagnosis. These tend to be slow-growing, gradually progressing over many years, even when metastatic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is extremely unlikely that any of the other cancers would not have shown substantial progression of disease in this time-frame. \u003Cstrong\u003EGastric adenocarcinoma and hepatocellular carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E are rapidly progressive cancers with a high annual mortality rate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere is no evidence of any lung or kidney lesion on CT scan, making this unlikely to be \u003Cstrong\u003Esquamous cell carcinoma of the lung\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003Erenal cell carcinoma \u003C/strong\u003Erespectively, even though these cancers can metastasise to the liver.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Grade 1 neuroendocrine tumours are slow-growing and can be medically managed. Patients can remain stable for years, with a \u003E80% 5-year survival rate."],"references":["Shebani KO, Souba WW, Finkelstein DM, Stark PC, Elgadi KM, Tanabe KK, Ott MJ. Prognosis and survival in patients with gastrointestinal tract carcinoid tumors. Ann Surg. 1999 Jun;229(6):815-21. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/10363895/","Cingam SR, Kashyap S, Karanchi H. Carcinoid Tumors. [Updated 2020 Jul 18]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2021 Jan-. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK448101/","NeuroEndocrine Cancer Australia. Neuroendocrine Cancer Prognosis. [Accessed 18/8/24]. Available at: https://neuroendocrine.org.au/prognosis/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80338"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"547"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15311"},{"type":"media","id":"15312"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15311","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15311"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/a313fd0b-fa75-4ce5-993f-39befc0adc77.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/a313fd0b-fa75-4ce5-993f-39befc0adc77.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":543,"height":476}},{"type":"media","id":"15312","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15312"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/d98cc11d-4887-4219-80e0-b6b61dd00da3.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/d98cc11d-4887-4219-80e0-b6b61dd00da3.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":365,"height":586}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80338","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/80338"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-09T10:22:13+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-09T10:22:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"547"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97783"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"it